'''''African Jazz Mokili Mobimba''''' (often referred to as '''''Africa Mokili Mobimba''''' or '''''Afrika Mokili Mobimba''''') was a popular song written in the [[Congolese rumba]] style by [[Mwamba Mongala]] and performed by [[Joseph Kabasele]]'s band, [[Le Grand Kallé et l'African Jazz|African Jazz]].

== History ==
[[File:African Jazz in 1961.jpg|thumb|African Jazz in a recording studio in 1961]]
Beginning in June 1961, the popular Congolese band [[Le Grand Kallé et l'African Jazz|African Jazz]] —led by [[Joseph Kabasele]]— made a series of recordings in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]. One of their new songs was "''African Jazz Mokili Mobimba''" (meaning "African Jazz all over the world"), written by guitarist [[Mwamba Mongala|Mwamba "Déchaud" Mongala]]<ref name= stewart97>{{harvnb|Stewart|2003|p=97}}</ref> in the [[Congolese rumba]] style.<ref name= Christgau193/> It was released later that year.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.digitalcongo.net/article/76817| title = Joseph Kabasele Tshiamala, le héros national congolais de la musique| date = 4 July 2011| website = Digital Congo| access-date = 27 March 2017| language = French| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170328195350/https://www.digitalcongo.net/article/76817| archive-date = 2017-03-28| dead-url = yes| df = }}</ref> It was a [[pastiche]] of two Latin American songs.<ref>{{harvnb|Bemba|1984|p=130}}</ref> The lyrics caution against excessive travel abroad.<ref>{{harvnb|ACCSA|1995|p=8}}</ref> The song also references all of the performing musicians as well as several Congolese cities and African countries (a common way of expressing praise at the time). At just over five minutes in length, it was one of the first African recordings to make use of the larger [[Single (music)#7-inch format|45 rpm record]]s then only recently available in the continent.<ref name= stewart97/>

''African Jazz Mokili Mobimba'' went on to become a hit of the early 1960s.<ref name= woodard64/> It became particularly popular in Kenyan dance clubs in 1965.<ref name= aai44>{{harvnb|African-American Institute|1975|p=44}}</ref> It is often considered to be one of African Jazz's most memorable songs, though by the early 2000s it was commonly referred to as simply "''Africa Mokili Mobimba''".<ref name= stewart97/>

== Cover versions ==
In 1994 the song was covered by ex-[[OK Jazz]] musician [[Sam Mangwana]] and the [[Fania All-Stars]] for the former's album, entitled ''Rumba Music''.<ref name= Christgau193>{{harvnb|Christgau|2000|p=193}}</ref> African Jazz vocalist [[Tabu Ley Rochereau]] later recorded "African Jazz Mokili Mobimba" as a solo artist to be the leading track on his 1996 live album ''Africa Worldwide''.<ref name= woodard64>{{harvnb|Woodard|1996|p=64}}</ref><ref name= stewart390>{{harvnb|Stewart|2003|p=390}}</ref> Ex-OK Jazz guitarist [[Papa Noel Nedule]] frequently featured Mangwana and Rochereau in his covers of the song.<ref>{{harvnb|C. Parker|2007|p=181}}</ref>

