__NOTOC__ {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Soviet philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |name = Alexander Spirkin |birth_date = {{Birth date|1918|12|24|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Saratov Governorate]], [[Russian SFSR]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|6|28|1918|12|24}} |death_place = Moscow, Russia |school_tradition = [[Marxism]] |main_interests = [[Dialectical materialism]], [[Psychology]], philosophical problems of [[cybernetics]] |notable_ideas = |influences = |influenced = |signature = |signature_alt = }} '''Alexander Spirkin''' ({{lang-ru|Алекса́ндр Гео́ргиевич Спи́ркин}}; 1918–2004) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russia]]n philosopher and psychologist. He was born in [[Saratov Governorate]] and graduated from the [[Moscow State Pedagogical University]]. In 1959 he received his doctorate in philosophy for a dissertation on the origin of consciousness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.i-u.ru/biblio/persons.aspx?id=1484 |title=Спиркин Александр Георгиевич |accessdate=2011-01-15 |year= |publisher=Russian Internet University for the Humanities |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930142138/http://www.i-u.ru/biblio/persons.aspx?id=1484 |archivedate=2011-09-30 }}</ref> He became a professor in 1970, and a year later was elected Vice-President of the USSR Philosophical Society. On November 26, 1974, Alexander Spirkin became a Corresponding Member of the [[USSR Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ras.ru/win/db/show_per.asp?P=.id-2337.ln-ru.dl-.pr-inf.uk-12 | title = Alexander Spirkin’s biography | accessdate = 2011-01-15 | year = | publisher = [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] }}</ref> His principal works deal with the problems of consciousness and self-consciousness, worldview, and the subject matter, structure and functions of philosophy. Prof. Spirkin’s ''Fundamentals of Philosophy'' (1988; English translation 1990) expounding [[Marxism–Leninism|Marxist–Leninist]] philosophy<ref>viz., dialectical and historical materialism.</ref> in popular form was awarded a prize at a competition of textbooks for students of higher educational establishments.
